SUMMARY:Yom HahShoah Program: After the Holocaust: Family History\, Memory
 \, and Identity 
DTSTART;TZID=America/New_York:20260415T191500
DTEND;TZID=America/New_York:20260415T210000
DTSTAMP:20260328T020314Z
UID:TU2065829319
RECURRENCE-ID;TZID=America/New_York:20260415T191500
SEQUENCE:0
CATEGORIES:Events
CLASS:PUBLIC
CREATED:20260323T165547Z
DESCRIPTION:**Community Program:**   \n7:15PM: Light Meal  \n7:40PM - 9:00
 PM: Program  \n  \n**After the Holocaust:** **Family History\, Memory\, an
 d Identity**  \nIn the aftermath of World War II\, Jewish survivors in Dis
 placed Persons (DP) camps rebuilt their lives with remarkable resilience\,
  creating families and ushering in an unprecedented baby boom. At the same
  time\, family memory—preserved through stories\, documents\, and tradit
 ions—became a powerful means of reconstructing identity after profound l
 oss. In this lecture\, Dr. Serafima Velkovich explores how family history 
 research and personal narratives intersect with the history of DP camps an
 d demonstrates how individuals can uncover traces of former DP babies with
 in their own family histories.  \n  \n*Join a conversation with Dr. Sera V
 elkovich of Yad Vashem and Shirley Grill of Shomrei Emunah as they explore
  the resilience\, and rebuilding of lives in the aftermath of the Shoah.*\
 n\n
LAST-MODIFIED:20260324T165806Z
TRANSP:OPAQUE
URL;VALUE=URI:https://teamup.com/kstx8swyw669kakgqa/events/2065829319
X-SOURCE:Congregation Shomrei Emunah
X-SOURCE-URL:https://shomrei.org/calendar/
END:VEVENT
